00:50:12.550 --> 00:50:13.180
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:50:13.180 --> 00:50:16.940
But if you're interested in only
the decay of an excited state,

00:50:16.940 --> 00:50:19.280
it can decay in
many, many modes,

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:25.560
but all these different
modes provide a contribution

00:50:25.560 --> 00:50:27.250
to the decay rate gamma.

00:50:27.250 --> 00:50:31.100
So at the end of the day, you
have a Hamiltonian evolution

00:50:31.100 --> 00:50:32.670
with a damping time gamma.

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:38.280
And this damping time gamma is
the sum of the other states.

00:50:38.280 --> 00:50:45.850
So in other words, the loss
of population from the excited

00:50:45.850 --> 00:50:50.660
state, you just incorporate
it by adding a damping time

00:50:50.660 --> 00:50:54.920
to the Schrodinger
equation because you're not

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:59.930
keeping track of the other
modes where the population goes.

00:50:59.930 --> 00:51:01.550
You're not keeping track.

00:51:01.550 --> 00:51:04.860
You just say, excited
state is lost.

00:51:04.860 --> 00:51:07.040
You're not interested
whether the atoms are now

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:08.990
in the ground state
or some other state.

00:51:08.990 --> 00:51:13.750
All you are describing the loss
rate from the excited state.

00:51:13.750 --> 00:51:17.930
And this is possible
by simply doing--

00:51:17.930 --> 00:51:20.120
by adding damping terms to
the Schrodinger equation.

00:51:25.410 --> 00:51:28.230
In other words, what I'm saying
is actually fairly simple.

00:51:28.230 --> 00:51:30.500
If you have a coherent
state and you lose it,

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:31.630
you just lose amplitude.

00:51:31.630 --> 00:51:33.200
what is left is coherent.

00:51:33.200 --> 00:51:35.200
When it's gone, it's gone.

00:51:35.200 --> 00:51:38.290
You have a smaller amplitude,
smaller probability.

00:51:38.290 --> 00:51:40.070
And that's simple to describe.

00:51:40.070 --> 00:51:44.110
What is harder to describe
is if you accumulate

00:51:44.110 --> 00:51:47.420
population in the ground
state and the population

00:51:47.420 --> 00:51:49.960
arrives in incoherent pieces.

00:51:49.960 --> 00:51:53.480
How to treat that, this
is more complicated.

00:51:53.480 --> 00:51:55.960
But simply the decay
of a pure state,

00:51:55.960 --> 00:51:58.530
it's just-- you have e
to the i omega t, which

00:51:58.530 --> 00:52:01.460
is a coherent evolution, and
then you add an imaginary part

00:52:01.460 --> 00:52:03.940
and this is a damping time.

00:52:03.940 --> 00:52:07.220
So what I'm saying,
it's sort of subtle

00:52:07.220 --> 00:52:10.171
but it's also very trivial.

00:52:10.171 --> 00:52:12.045
I don't know if this
addresses your question.

00:52:15.900 --> 00:52:19.330
In the end, in general
